div.h2: Real Mode Protected Mode: The Critical Transition

p.strong: The far jump is mandatory it is not ceremony

g.text: GDT (loaded via lgdt before CR0.PE set)
What happens if you omit the far jump?

div.p: SCHIZOPHRENIC HALF-STATE CR0.PE=1 hardware expects protected-mode semantics CS still = 0x0000 real-mode segment value, not a GDT selector

p.strong: The far jump does THREE things atomically:

ol.li: Loads CS 0x08 CPU validates 0x08 against GDT[1] (kernel code descriptor) Descriptor cache updated: base=0, limit=4GB, DPL=0, executable
Loads EIP protected_entry address EIP now points to the first true 32-bit protected-mode instruction

Flushes the instruction prefetch queue All speculatively-decoded real-mode bytes are discarded CPU re-fetches from the new CS:EIP using PM semantics Without this far jump: CPU tries to decode next byte with stale real-mode pipeline state #GP (General Protection Fault) IDT not set up yet #DF (Double Fault) Double fault handler not set up Triple Fault CPU RESET Machine reboots silently. No error message. Ever.

div.p: STABLE STATE CPU fully in 32-bit Protected Mode All registers using GDT-backed segment descriptors Prefetch queue contains valid 32-bit PM instructions

g.text: GDT[1] Kernel Code CS=0x08 points here

ol.li: CPU executes mov cr0, eax CR0.PE=1
Next instruction fetched: CS=0x0000 (real-mode value) CPU tries to validate 0x0000 as a protected-mode selector
GDT[0] = Null descriptor #GP (General Protection Fault, vector 13)
IDT not yet loaded CPU tries to use IVT (real-mode interrupt table) In protected mode, address 0x0000 is interpreted as an IDT gate descriptor #DF (Double Fault, vector 8)
Double fault handler also invalid Triple Fault

CPU asserts RESET pin Machine reboots silently You will see no error message. The QEMU window will flash. Without -no-reboot, the cycle repeats endlessly. Add: qemu-system-i386 -d int,cpu_reset -no-reboot to observe.

div.p: STALE / DANGEROUS Instructions decoded using real-mode address semantics:
[0x7E1C] jmp far 0x08:0x7E20 next instruction (not yet fetched) [0x7E18] mov cr0, eax just executed [0x7E14] or eax, 0x1 already retired

If the CPU fetched anything past mov cr0, eax speculatively, those bytes were decoded as 16-bit real-mode. In PM they will be reinterpreted incorrectly unless the pipeline is flushed this is WHY the far jump is mandatory.

Addressing formula still active in pipeline: physical = CS 16 + offset = 0x0000 16 + EIP = EIP (flat, 20-bit) Hardware reality (CR0.PE=1): MMU now expects GDT lookup for CS contradiction between pipeline state and hardware expectation General Protection Fault #13 on next instruction if not resolved

g.text: DS / ES / SS / FS / GS (must reload)

div.p: FLUSHED & REFILLED 32-bit PM decoded bytes nasm [protected_entry+0] mov ax, 0x10 ; executing now [protected_entry+3] mov ds, ax [protected_entry+5] mov es, ax [protected_entry+7] mov ss, ax [protected_entry+9] mov esp, 0x9FC00 [protected_entry+14] call kernel_main
All instructions decoded with 32-bit default operand size. No stale real-mode bytes remain in the pipeline.

Address translation formula (flat model): linear_addr = GDT[CS.index].base + EIP = 0x00000000 + EIP = EIP Segmentation is a no-op in the flat model. The interesting protection check is the DPL comparison: CS.DPL = 0 ring 0 (kernel) CPL (from CS bits 0-1) = 0 kernel mode confirmed Every load/store similarly validated through DS descriptor.

New formula: linear = Seg.base + offset For flat model: linear = 0 + offset = offset Physical = linear (paging disabled until Milestone 3) Protection enforced on every access: Limit check: offset segment limit Privilege check: CPL DPL for data, CPL = DPL for stack Type check: code segments are not writable
Selector: 0x00 All fields = 0. CPU raises #GP if loaded into CS/DS. Required by architecture spec (must be first entry).
Selector: 0x08 (index=1, TI=0, RPL=0) Base: 0x00000000 Limit: 0xFFFFF (4KB = 4GB) Access byte: 0x9A = P=1, DPL=0, S=1, E=1, R=1 Flags: 0xC = G=1 (4KB granularity), D=1 (32-bit)
Selector: 0x10 (index=2, TI=0, RPL=0) Base: 0x00000000 Limit: 0xFFFFF (4KB = 4GB) Access byte: 0x92 = P=1, DPL=0, S=1, E=0, W=1 Flags: 0xC = G=1, D=1 (32-bit)
Selector: 0x1B (index=3, TI=0, RPL=3) Access byte: 0xFA = P=1, DPL=3, S=1, E=1, R=1 Used in Milestone 4 for ring-3 user processes.
Selector: 0x23 (index=4, TI=0, RPL=3) Access byte: 0xF2 = P=1, DPL=3, S=1, E=0, W=1 Used in Milestone 4 for ring-3 user data.
Bits 153: Index = 1 GDT[1] Bit 2: TI = 0 GDT (not LDT) Bits 10: RPL = 0 Requested Privilege Level = ring 0
Bit 31 (PG): 0 paging OFF Bit 0 (PE): 1 PROTECTED MODE SET Value: 0x00000001
CS = 0x0000 (real-mode paragraph value) Descriptor cache still holds real-mode semantics: Base = 0x00000 Limit = 0xFFFF (64 KB, 16-bit limit) DPL = 0 NOT a valid protected-mode selector
DS = ES = SS = 0x0000 All using real-mode 64 KB window semantics Will break on first data access in PM
EIP 0x7E1C (points to instruction AFTER mov cr0, eax) CPU is about to fetch next instruction at CS:EIP = 0x0000 16 + 0x7E1C = physical 0x7E1C
Bit 31 (PG): 0 paging still OFF (Milestone 3) Bit 0 (PE): 1 Protected Mode active Value: 0x00000001

CS = 0x08 (GDT index 1, RPL=0) Descriptor cache updated by far jump: Base = 0x00000000 (flat, all 4 GB) Limit = 0xFFFFFFFF (4 GB) DPL = 0 (ring 0 / kernel) Type = Code, readable, non-conforming Valid protected-mode kernel code selector

Still hold stale real-mode descriptor cache values! NEXT instructions must be: nasm mov ax, 0x10 ; kernel data selector mov ds, ax mov es, ax mov ss, ax mov fs, ax mov gs, ax mov esp, 0x9FC00 ; 32-bit stack
Until these execute, data segment accesses use the old 64KB real-mode descriptor cache window.
EIP = address of protected_entry label Now a full 32-bit offset into the CS segment (base=0, so physical = EIP directly)

text.tspan: CS:EIP used to fill prefetch queue
